@NODE "WhatWhy" "Whats this program for?"

 3. What does it do and why ?

Every  library,  and  some  devices  have a table of pointers to the routines
contained  within  them.  Each entry in this table is six bytes long.  If the
routine  they  point  to is 6 bytes long (Or less) it will be copied into the
jump-table to increase system speed a little.  Also, if the first instruction
is a jump to a second instruction, then the address of the second instruction
is inserted into the jumptable.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Requirements" "What you need."

 4. Requirements.

 To Run StreamLineOS you will need...

 * At least V37 of the Operating System.
   I  had just *One* request for me to support v1.x Of the OS, which to me is
   just  more  effort  than  it's worth.  Everyone else has upgraded.  If you
   haven't, then more fool you.

 * If you use one of my other patches `FasterForbid', then you may remove it,
   as this patch does the same thing, AND MORE!

No other requirements whatsoever.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Usage" "What to do."

 5.Usage.

The 1.x version of SLOS was meant to be run once at bootup, and maybe once or
twice  an hour (If you felt like it) to keep system speed at a maximum.  Now,
with the 2.x, I present a resident version.

The  2.x  series  uses a commodity to stay resident.  By using the `Exchange'
program,  you  can at any time enable/disable SLOS, remove it, or call up the
GUI program by pressing the SHOW INTERFACE button.

*NB*
 You may also simply run the `SYS:Tools/StreamLineOS2' program.

The commodity also has two hotkeys.

1. `Streamline Entire System'.
   Default is ctrl left alt & s
   You may change this by changing the STREAMLINEHOTKEY argument/tooltype.

2. Pop-up GUI.
   Default is ctrl right alt & s
   You may change this by changing the CX_POPKEY argument/tooltype.
   * Note also, that the GUIPATH argument/tooltype must also be set correctly
   for  this  function  to  work.   If  GUIPATH  is  not  set, it defaults to
   SYS:Tools/StreamLineOS2


Documentation  of  the  GUI program will be found in the file SlosPrefs.Guide
which  is  currently  unwritten,  as  it  is  incomplete.   As  it  continues
development,  docs  will  be  written.   It  is currently included merely for
examining the Listview results, and for completeness.

Server Arguments: (Tooltypes & Shell args)

QUIET             Suppresses text output. (No effect on WorkBench)
NORESIDENT        Tells SLOS to Quit immediately after streamlining.
GUIPATH           Tells SLOS where the GUI program is located.
STREAMLINEHOTKEY  Defines the hotkey used to StreamLine on demand.
CX_POPKEY         Defines the hotkey used to popup the GUI.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Bugs" "Known Bugs/Incompatabilities."

 6.Bugs!

* Your VirusKiller/Monitor Program
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  May  report some strange addresses in it's Libvector reading, this is a bug
  in  the VirusKiller, due to the programmer not checking that there is a JMP
  instruction, and just assuming that there will be a valid address two bytes
  from the library LVO point.
  SLOS modifies the following vectors:
    exec.library:    _LVOInitResident()
    exec.library:    _LVOSetFunction()

* CacheFont
  ~~~~~~~~~
  If run this patch twice while running SLOS, it will install twice.
  The  author  was  very  silly, and CacheFont recognises itself in memory by
  placing  two  NOP  instructions  at  the  entrypoint  of  a  vector  in the
  diskfont.library.  These get optimised away by SLOS.

* SetFunction() managers.
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  Running  patches  like  SetManager  may  be unreliable, as they replace the
  SetFunction  vector  with  it's  own  code  which  never calls the original
  function.   If  you  experience  incompatabilities, mail the author of your
  SetMan  clone,  and  tell  him  to  contact  me to find out how to make his
  patch-manager support SLOS's features.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "TechnicalInfo" "Technical Information."

 7. Technical Information.

* How exactly does this work?
  StreamLineOS  searches  through the resident library, devices and resources
  lists, Opening each one in turn, optimises it, and then closes it.  It also
  patches  the  InitResident  vector  of  exec.library,  so that it can catch
  libraries,  devices  &  resources  as and when they are loaded.  Using this
  vector  instead  of  using  (for  example)  OpenLibrary means that once the
  library  has  been  opened  once,  it won't get reoptimised with subsequent
  openings, unless it gets flushed from memory.

* What instructions does it optimise?
  @{"Click here for indepth instructions list" LINK "Opcodes"}

* StreamLineOS is Coded in 100% Assembly Language for speed and compact size.

* Contains  100%  PC  relative code, which means it will load at any address
  without any need for relocation.  Let's see `C' coders write a program like
  that!

* Will free any opened libraries/devices and exit gracefully on Failure/Exit.
  You can even flush the streamlineos.library while SLOS is running.  It will
  open, use and close it as and when it needs it.

* Requires no extra memory for however many patches it makes.

* Has been tested extensively with ...
   - Enforcer v37.70
   - Mungwall v37.71
   - CodeWatcher.
   - Several CBM `Strain' type tools (Low-mem, low CPU-time e.t.c.)
   - Several personal debugging tools.

* Has had extensive testing by myself and my ever faithful army of
  ßeta-testers on all sorts of varying configurations of Amiga, who will
  be sure to let me know if there are any problems [I HOPE!] ;-Ţ

* Has been developed on an a A1200, fitted with
   - GVP 1230-II accelerator (50Mhz 68030,MMU, 4mb of 32 bit 60ns fastram)
   - 3.5" IBM 525Mb IDE Harddisk.

* The patches made by StreamLineOS cannot be undone.

* This is the most important one! ;^)

                Move.l  #"SLOW",d0
                And.b   #$FB,d0

* No Animals were harmed during the making of this program.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Opcodes" "Opcodes known"

  If it finds a routine whose first instruction is an unconditional
  branch to another memory region.
  Routines such as...

        JSR $xxxxxxxx
        RTS

        JMP $xxxxxxxx

        BRA $xxxxxxxx

        BSR $xxxxxxxx
        RTS

        PEA $xxxxxxxx
        RTS

        MOVE.L #$xxxxxxxx,-(SP)
        RTS

  Then  it will calculate this second address, and store it in the jumptable,
  so  all  calls to this library routine will go straight to the code instead
  of  all this pointless jumping around!  SLOS will also handle nested jumps,
  No need to run SLOS twice.
  This Kangaroo-code is surprisingly, quite frequently found.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
  If  the routine exits immediately (An RTS) then this RTS is copied into the
  vector table.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
  If  the  routine  is  three words long or less, (Including the RTS) then it
  will copied directly into the vector table.
  Routines such as...

        Moveq   #n,d0
        Rts

        Clr.l   Dn              (This actually gets optimised to a Moveq)
        Rts

        Move.l  Register,Register
        Rts

        Addq.x  #n,??           (Not performed if destination=memory address)
        Rts

        Subq.x  #n,??           (Not performed if destination=memory address)
        Rts

        Move.l nn(Ax),-(SP)
        Rts

        Move.l Reg,nn(Ax)
        Rts

        Move.l nn(Ax),Dn
        Rts

        Move.l nn(Ax),An
        Rts

        BClr #n,Dn
        Rts                         (If n<15 this becomes And.w #$FFFF~n,Dn)

        BChg #n,Dn
        Rts                         (If n<15 this becomes Eor.w #1<<n,Dn)

        BSet #n,Dn
        Rts                         (If n<15 this becomes Or.w  #1<<n,Dn)

        And.x #n,??                 (x = word or byte)
        Rts

        Jsr nn(An),RTS

        The 32/64 bit math instructions..
         muls.l  D1,D0
         mulu.l  D1,D0
         divsl.l D1,D1:D0
         divul.l D1,D1:D0
         muls.l  D1,D1:D0
         mulu.l  D1,D1:D0

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
I spotted this silly sequence in intuition library..

                Movem.l a0-a1,-(SP)
                Jsr     Routine
                Addq.l  #8,SP
                Rts
                ...
Routine:        Rts

An RTS is placed into the Jumptable.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Future" "What I intend to do."

 9. Future.

* Fixing of any bug reports.

* Adding more optimisation types.

* Version 3.0 Of SLOS will consider a new approach which will allow
  a fairly big optimisation to take place. Converting JMP's to BRA.L's
  (Which of course is 68020+ only) Currently doing such an operation
  makes the system too unstable.

* Implementing a more sophisticated disassembly routine to decipher
  the code the JMP points to, and move the 3 words into the Jumptable
  as long as the code..
              a. doesn't access PC relative data.
              b. doesn't Bcc to another address.
              c. terminates properly. (Ie, RTS or JMP/BRA in 3 words
                  somewhere)
@ENDNODE

@NODE "AboutAuthor" "Information about me."

 10. About the Author.

Born : 6th Feb 1974) -- Which makes me at least 23.
Job  : HND Software Engineering Student.

I've  been  developing software on the Amiga since 1990, although a lot of it
was  never  released  (Phew..) I was a commercial programmer for a while, but
things turned sour, and I turned to Shareware programming.

I'm  currently  working  on  quite a few projects, of which SLOS is taking up
most  of  my  time.   I'm also helping out a few shareware friends with their
programs.


Other releases by me...

